TY  - JOUR
T1  - Experimental Analysis of Neighborhood Effects
AU  - Kling, Jeffrey R
AU  - Liebman, Jeffrey B
AU  - Katz, Lawrence F
Y1  - 2007/01/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/01/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0262.2007.00733.x
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 83
EP  - 119
VL  - 75
IS  - 1
KW  - Social experiment
KW  - housing vouchers
KW  - neighborhoods
KW  - mental health
KW  - urban poverty
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-0262.2007.00733.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Families, primarily female-headed minority households with children, living in high-poverty public housing projects in five U.S. cities were offered housing vouchers by lottery in the Moving to Opportunity program. Four to seven years after random assignment, families offered vouchers lived in safer neighborhoods that had lower poverty rates than those of the control group not offered vouchers. We find no significant overall effects of this intervention on adult economic self-sufficiency or physical health. Mental health benefits of the voucher offers for adults and for female youth were substantial. Beneficial effects for female youth on education, risky behavior, and physical health were offset by adverse effects for male youth. For outcomes that exhibit significant treatment effects, we find, using variation in treatment intensity across voucher types and cities, that the relationship between neighborhood poverty rate and outcomes is approximately linear.
ER  - 

